body:
Thanks for working on this @BasPH 

I believe that `yesterday_ds` does not make sense since we cannot assume that the schedule is daily. I don't see any usage of this variable. Personally I do use `next_execution_date` quite extensively. When you have a job that runs daily, but you want to change this to an hourly job. In such a case you don't want to change `{{ (execution_date + macros.timedelta(days=1)) }}` to `{{ (execution_date + macros.timedelta(hours=1)) }}`everywhere.

@bolkedebruin What was your plan with the `{in,out}lets`?

@kaxil I apply all your suggestion. In addition, I changed all `literalinclude` to `exampleinclude`, so full code of example is available now. :-) 
Reference: 
https://github.com/apache/airflow/pull/4894

@alikemalocalan Have you finished your work? I have been watching your work for a long time. I think  it will be a good idea to call PMC so that they look at the change. They have the power to accept this change. I am only a normal user without specific permission. 

I would like to thank you for your commitment to this project. People create this project and they are the greatest value in this project. 

Is there anything I can help you with?  I personally do not use the Azure cloud, but the sustainable development of the project is important to me.

What do you think about adding support for Python 3.6?  I personally have concerns between testing only on one version of Python. This can cause a compatibility problem. 

@potiuk You have extensive experience with incompatibility problems between these two versions. Can you tell us more? 

My comment should not be treated as opposed to this change. The new version of Python can be introduced in a separate PR.

@jrans Myabe there should be a discussion if a change is needed in the hook or in the operators.
There is a ticket with similar report https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/AIRFLOW-3972
In any case you are welcome to submit PR.
